Files:
- platform/cli/src/commands/status.ts

Context:
The status command renders a text summary then appends a block listing all disabled tool names. This block is confusing — it floods the screen when the user just wants to see if the server is healthy.

Code to remove (lines 196-205 approximately):
```typescript
const disabledBrowserTools = Array.isArray(data.disabledBrowserTools)
  ? (data.disabledBrowserTools as string[])
  : [];
if (disabledBrowserTools.length > 0) {
  console.log('');
  console.log(pc.bold('  Disabled Browser Tools'));
  for (const name of disabledBrowserTools) {
    console.log(`    ${pc.red(name)}`);
  }
}
```
Delete this block entirely. Do NOT change the JSON output path (which already has browserToolNames in it).

Constraints:
- Do NOT change status --json output
- Do NOT remove the numeric 'Browser tools: 76' count from the text summary
- Do NOT change the 'Disabled Browser Tools' concept elsewhere — only remove it from status text output

Files:
- platform/cli/src/commands/audit.ts

Context:
There are two handlers: handleAuditFromFile (reads from disk log) and handleAudit (calls server). Both have the same pattern:
```typescript
const hasFilters = options.plugin || options.tool || options.since;
if (hasFilters) {
  console.log(pc.dim('No entries match the current filters. Try broadening the search.'));
} else {
  console.log(pc.dim('No audit entries found. Invoke tools through an MCP client to generate audit entries.'));
}
```
This appears at approximately line 191-197 (handleAuditFromFile) and lines 282-289 (handleAudit server path).

Fix: Remove the hasFilters branching and always use:
```typescript
console.log(pc.dim('No audit entries found. Invoke tools through an MCP client to generate audit entries.'));
```

Rationale: The 'broaden the search' message implies data exists. When no audit file exists or no tools have been invoked, data does NOT exist. Using the same message in all empty-state cases is accurate and less confusing.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the error message when the audit file is missing entirely ('No audit log file found at ...')
- Do NOT change behavior for the --json path (which returns [])
- Apply the fix to BOTH the file-path handler and the server-path handler
